    I basically cut all campaigns down to the best performing lander since I felt like I had enough data for each and thus ROI sky-rocketed
    Sometimes this is the right thing to do. When you really see one element clearly winning over the others, it's time to give it all the volume and stress-test it to confirm the performance. This will often result in lower performance, but in specific cases it confirms the theory and you end up with a killed lander, AD or whatever it is that you test.

    I got a bit scared so I cut my bid/budgets across the board too since I didn't want to go over cap - was actually quite foolish in retrospect since I didn't hit anywhere near and the low bids really cut down my traffic
    As twinaxe mentioned, it's usually OK to shoot over the cap a BIT. I'm not saying to send 200 leads if the cap is 100, but something like 120 shouldn't really cause issues. And you can always blame it on the time zone difference... we are talking about 24 hours frame, which can result in very different results, based on what time zone you chose Do not over-use this, but I've used it as an argument a few times already

    Originally Posted by fastaj
    You are right, it's a weird mental block since I feel like scared of scaling and want to diversify and get more offers since I've read so many people with FA and when they finally start making $XXX or even $XXXX per day figures with one offer it eventually gets pulled and they get completely wiped out.
    There is a fine line here and there are 2 important things to keep in mind, ALWAYS.

    1. Every offer will die at some point, so you simply need to milk it as long as it works.
    2. Since every offer will die at some point, you need to have a backup plan once that happens, so you need to keep on testing at all times.

    The important thing is to make sure you are still seeing profits. So running an offer and making $200 profit per day and losing $200 on new tests at the same time, that's not a good strategy.
    At the same time, testing a lot and allocating too much funds to testing and then missing the resources in the campaigns you want to scale, that's not a good idea either.

    Always dedicate majority of your budget to run campaigns that work at the biggest possible scale. A reinvest part of your profits into finding new offers.

    I always try to scale a profitable offer as soon as I manage to optimize it... I'm not trying to reach perfection, as soon as the profits look decent I scale the fuck out of it With a bit more optimization, my ROI would probably be better, but I would likely lose a few days of runtime, since as we already know, the offer can go down anytime.

    You are right, it's a weird mental block since I feel like scared of scaling and want to diversify and get more offers since I've read so many people with FA and when they finally start making $XXX or even $XXXX per day figures with one offer it eventually gets pulled and they get completely wiped out.
    I totally understand your concerns but it´s often easier to scale something where you already know that it works instead of testing something new where the outcome is uncertain.

    But as matuloo said, sooner or later every offer dies so a good way is to send few % of your traffic to new offers to test so when your main offer dies you ideally already have a replacement offer ready.



    About scaling, a good way is to take good converting placements from high activity or fresh user campaigns and run them as whitelist in lower activity or older user freshness.

    When the offer allows it you can also try to open the targeting to receive more volume.

    And taking a good converting funnel to other traffisources can also help to

    A.) Scale the campaign
    and
    B.) Have an easier start at a new source

    Thought I'd give an update, been a bit too long.

    I'll keep it brief, mostly focused around what on my mind the past 2 weeks

    Cash Flow:
    I'm now on weekly/fortnightly payments on all the ANs which I'm running traffic on, this has alleviated cashflow pressure that had been building up, where I had to float more than I was comfortable.

    Still, cashflow management is a skill, not a super complicated one but mostly focused around diligence, I'm stilling running "hot" but now I'm at least not hamstrung waiting for payments and having to pause traffic on green camps - which SUCKS.

    Relationships:
    Eye has turned more onto relationships, hard to establish meaningful personal connection since travel is restricted and there is no in-person element, however I'm treating this more as a "real business" that has reputation for professionalism.

    Working with new networks and discussing with offer owners, which brings me onto my next point

    Direct vs Network:
    I've been give a lot of good advice, advocating for both sides.

    Running direct has a lot of advantages - moats, stability, transparency.

    Running with a network also has a lot of advantages - quicker payouts, insurance against being stiffed (most of the time), speed of execution, industry insights.

    Sticking to networks for now, but dipping my toes into potential direct deals, lot of upside but cashflow will once again become an issue if I dive head-first.

    Niching down:
    The way to go, no question. Pick an evergreen niche and stick to it, higher success rate, more reputational effects, much deeper knowledge.

    After speaking to some affiliates doing xxxx/day figures profit, common theme is that they are all niched into 1 vertical and maybe a few geos.

    Time Management:
    Struggling with consistency, need to figure out a proper routine - I think developing some kind of daily plan would help, anyone have any tips/examples?

    Also I'm still working a 9 to 5, I like my job well enough and time isn't as much of an issue right now, but if I end up building a small team - which I may end up doing it'll become a much bigger issue to juggle.

    Life-style inflation:
    I haven't gone all out with getting a lambo or whatever but it's nice to worry a bit less about money and buying small useful stuff I would think 10x times about before. I don't want to waste money because I feel like any $1 I waste will be a lot more than $1 due lost returns from my business.

    Great update and lot's for truth in everything you posted

    Struggling with consistency, need to figure out a proper routine - I think developing some kind of daily plan would help, anyone have any tips/examples?
    I still don't have a proper system in place, after all those years, but that's probably because I'm pretty ok with working in a "chaotic" way... I guess it has something to do with the fact that I have 3 kids... not much planning possible when you have little kids around, you just do what is needed

    So basically, I only have a few "rules"

    - I keep renting an office, even though I could work from home and allocate the tasks to my biz partner and the freelancers we use. I just figured out that it's a good idea to keep work separated from private life. I still do work from home in the evening, but the core of my tasks are sorted by the time I leave the office.

    - I've split my work day into several parts that I try to stick to... first thing I do in the morning (well morning, I go to bed late, so I rarely wake up before 9-10 am is checking stats, doing quick optimizations, pausing what needs pausing, messing with bids etc... Then we (me and my biz partner) talk about what to test/launch next or whether to just keep running what we have or maybe try to introduce new creatives etc... next is the lunch After the lunch we execute what we agreed on... so we talk to our designer and coder (if needed) and then setup new campaigns.

    This is a rough frame we try to follow... so stats checking and optimizations in the morning, then planning the next steps, break for lunch and then actually doing what we agreed to have done. Sometimes we decide not to make any new campaigns, so then we just kind of plan, read, network and check stats all the time... you know how it goes

    To be honest, we have tried to set precise plans and schedules and stick to it, but I personally didn't like it at all. One of the reasons I decided to stick with AM was the freedom it can provide, so having some strict plans or schedules somehow didn't click with me, I'm not that type of a person
